1. Introduction¶

1.1 Understanding the Problem¶

Fetal health is a critical aspect of maternal and neonatal care, as it directly impacts the well-being of both the mother and the unborn child. Detecting fetal health problems early is important for reducing the risk of newborn deaths, as many of these deaths can be prevented with timely medical care. During pregnancy, continuous monitoring of fetal well-being helps detect potential complications, such as fetal distress, abnormal heart rate patterns, and oxygen deprivation, which can lead to serious birth complications, including preterm labor or stillbirth, if not addressed in time.

Currently, fetal health assessment relies on cardiotocography (CTG), a simple and cost-effective method for monitoring fetal heart rate, uterine contractions, and other vital signs. However, manually interpreting CTG readings can be challenging and prone to human error, which may lead to the misclassification of high-risk cases. As a result, developing an automated system that can accurately classify fetal health into categories can assist healthcare professionals in making timely and informed decisions.

By leveraging deep learning techniques, fetal health classification can be improved through automated pattern recognition, enhancing diagnostic accuracy. An automated classification system can support healthcare professionals in making timely, data-driven decisions while also enabling early interventions that can prevent complications during labor and delivery, ultimately improving overall maternal and neonatal health outcomes.

1.2 Aims and Objectives¶

The aim of this project is to develop a Deep Learning Classification Model for fetal health assessment using Cardiotocography (CTG) data. The model will be designed to improve diagnostic accuracy and assist healthcare professionals in identifying high-risk cases, enabling timely medical interventions and potentially reducing neonatal complications.us results.

The objectives of this project are:

  • Analyze the dataset to understand its structure, distributions, and key patterns.
  • Preprocess the data by normalizing features, converting it into tensors, and splitting it into training, validation, and test sets.
  • Define the evaluation metrics and establish a naive baseline for comparison.
  • Develop a baseline model to set a reference performance for the task.
  • Train an overfitting model to observe its behavior and understand its limitations.
  • Apply regularization techniques and fine-tune hyperparameters to improve generalization.
  • Train and evaluate the optimized final model using the best hyperparameters.
  • Assess the final model’s performance on the test set and compare it with previous results.

1.3 About the Dataset¶

This study utilizes the Fetal Health Classification dataset dataset, originally sourced from The Journal of Maternal-Fetal Medicine and made publicly available by Andrew Mvd on Kaggle. The dataset consists of 2,126 records containing features extracted from Cardiotocography (CTG) exams. Each record has been classified by three expert obstetricians into one of three categories:

  • Normal: No signs of fetal distress
  • Suspect: Potential irregularities requiring further monitoring
  • Pathological: High-risk cases requiring immediate medical attention on

This dataset is highly suitable for this study as it provides comprehensive fetal health indicators, including fetal heartbeat data, along with accelerations, decelerations, and abnormal short-term and long-term variability. It also contains information on fetal movement and uterine contractions, which are crucial for assessing fetal oxygen levels and overall health. Additionally, the dataset provides statistical features such as the mean, median, variance, trend, number of peaks, and number of zero crossings in the exam’s histogram. Most importantly, the dataset includes a categorical label for fetal health, Ensuring that each record is accurately assigned to one of the three categories by medical experts.

2. Problem Definition and Dataset¶

In this section, we will define the problem statement, conduct an initial exploratory data analysis (EDA) to examine class balance and feature correlations, and identify potential challenges that may arise when using this dataset for our deep learning model.

2.1 Problem Statement¶

The model addresses the challenge of accurately identifying potential fetal distress by developing a deep learning model that automates the classification of fetal health status based on cardiotocography (CTG) data. By leveraging various fetal heart rate and uterine contraction features, the model can help medical professionals in diagnostics by predicting whether a fetus is in a normal, suspect, or pathological state.

This is a single-label, multi-class classification problem in which the model assigns one of three discrete labels to each input sample. It is designed to distinguish between different fetal health conditions based on the provided data. The model processes numerical features extracted from CTG exams and outputs a classification label indicating fetal health status as normal (1), suspect (2), or pathological (3).

2.2 Dataset Overview¶

This dataset consists of 2,126 records, which is generally considered small for deep learning models. A limited dataset size can negatively impact model performance by increasing the risk of overfitting and reducing generalization ability.

The dataset contains 22 features, extracted from Cardiotocography (CTG) exams, which provide key insights into fetal health. These features include:

  • baseline value – Baseline fetal heart rate (FHR)
  • accelerations – Number of accelerations per second
  • fetal_movement – Number of fetal movements per second
  • uterine_contractions – Number of uterine contractions per second
  • light_decelerations – Number of light decelerations per second
  • severe_decelerations – Number of severe decelerations per second
  • prolongued_decelerations – Number of prolonged decelerations per second
  • abnormal_short_term_variability – Percentage of time with abnormal short-term variability
  • mean_value_of_short_term_variability – Mean value of short-term variability
  • percentage_of_time_with_abnormal_long_term_variability – Percentage of time with abnormal long-term variability
  • mean_value_of_long_term_variability – Mean value of long-term variability
  • histogram_width – Width of the histogram generated from all values in a record
  • histogram_min – Minimum value in the histogram
  • histogram_max – Maximum value in the histogram
  • histogram_number_of_peaks – Number of peaks in the histogram
  • histogram_number_of_zeroes – Number of zeroes in the histogram
  • histogram_mode – Mode of the histogram
  • histogram_mean – Mean value of the histogram
  • histogram_median – Median value of the histogram
  • histogram_variance – Variance of the histogram
  • histogram_tendency – Trend of the histogram
  • fetal_health – Fetal health classification:
    • 1 – Normal
    • 2 – Suspect
    • 3 – Pathological

Next, we will explore the dataset further using the .info() and .describe() functions from the pandas library to gain insights into its structure and statistical properties.

2.4 Potential challenges¶

2.4.1 Class Imbalance¶

Since the dataset is imbalanced, it can lead to biased model predictions, where the model favors the majority class, resulting in poor generalization and high classification error rates for minority classes.To address this issue, class weights can be applied during training to ensure that the model treats all classes more equally. Additionally, accuracy should not be used as the primary evaluation metric, as a model can achieve high accuracy simply by predicting the majority class, making it a misleading measure of performance.

2.4.2 Noise in FHR Patterns¶

Fetal heart rate (FHR) patterns can be influenced by external factors such as maternal conditions, stress, fetal movement, and measurement errors, introducing noise into cardiotocography (CTG) readings. This variability can affect the model’s accuracy by making it harder to distinguish meaningful patterns from random fluctuations. Inconsistent sensor readings or external disturbances may lead to misclassifications, especially in borderline cases. To minimize the impact of noise, data preprocessing techniques such as normalization, outlier removal, or smoothing methods can be applied to improve model reliability.

2.4.3 Overfitting¶

Since this dataset is relatively small, it is susceptible to overfitting, where the model performs well on training data but struggles with new, unseen data. This leads to poor generalization and reduced transferability to real-world cases. When training on limited data, it is generally advisable to use a smaller neural network with only one or two hidden layers to minimize the risk of severe overfitting. Additionally, applying regularization techniques such as dropout, L2 weight decay, or data augmentation can further help improve model generalization.

2.4.4 Generalization¶

Since the dataset is relatively small, it may not cover all possible pregnancy conditions, which could limit the model’s ability to perform well on different populations. As a result, the model may learn patterns specific to this dataset rather than identifying generalizable features applicable to real-world cases. To improve generalization, techniques such as cross-validation, data augmentation, and regularization can help the model learn more robust and transferable patterns. Additionally, evaluating the model on an external dataset or expanding the dataset with more diverse samples can further enhance its real-world applicability.

3. Choosing a Measure of Success¶

Here, we will select the most appropriate metrics to effectively evaluate model performance and define what constitutes success. As mentioned earlier, since we are dealing with a class-imbalanced problem, standard accuracy is not a reliable metric as it can be misleading. Instead, we will use alternative evaluation metrics that provide a more balanced assessment of model performance.

3.1 Balanced Accuracy¶

Balanced accuracy is the arithmetic mean of sensitivity (recall for the positive class) and specificity (recall for the negative class). It is equivalent to the macro-average of recall scores across all classes, ensuring that each class contributes equally to the final score. This makes it particularly useful for imbalanced datasets, as it prevents the model from being biased toward the majority class by applying equal weight to all classes.The formula for Balanced Accuracy is:

Sensitivity, also known as the true positive rate (TPR) or recall, measures the proportion of actual positive cases that are correctly identified by the model. Specificity, also known as the true negative rate (TNR), measures the proportion of correctly identified negative cases over the total actual negatives. Both can be calculated using the following formulas:

Since achieving 100% balanced accuracy is nearly impossible and unrealistic, a reasonable goal for this task is to achieve a balanced accuracy above 80%, indicating that the model performs well across all classes without being biased toward the majority class.

3.2 Precision¶

Precision measures the proportion of correctly predicted positive cases out of all cases the model classified as positive. It provides insight into the model’s ability to accurately identify positive instances while minimizing false positives. The formula for precision is:

For this task, we aim to achieve a precision of over 80%, as this reflects a strong model with a low false positive rate.

3.3 Recall¶

Recall measures the proportion of correctly predicted positive cases out of all actual positive cases. It is a crucial metric in classification, especially for imbalanced datasets, as it evaluates the model’s ability to identify all relevant instances while minimizing false negatives. The formula for recall is:

Since precision and recall are closely related, we can also aim for a recall of over 80%, as this indicates that the model is successfully capturing most positive cases.

3.4 F1 Score¶

The F1 score is a widely used metric for assessing the performance of a classification model. It balances Precision and Recall, focusing on a single class rather than the entire dataset. It is computed using the following formula:

However, in the case of multi-class classification, we use Macro F1 score, which is the average of the F1 scores across all classes. 4. Deciding on an Evaluation Protocol¶

In this section, we will define the evaluation protocol to measure model performance and track progress. Choosing appropriate metrics and validation strategies ensures the model generalizes effectively while addressing challenges such as class imbalance and overfitting.

4.1 Stratified K-fold Cross Validation¶

Unlike standard k-fold cross-validation, which splits the data randomly and may result in imbalanced folds, stratified k-fold ensures that each fold maintains the same class distribution as the full dataset. This prevents the model from overfitting to majority classes and improves generalization to unseen cases. By applying stratification, the model learns from diverse yet balanced subsets of the data, leading to a more stable and reliable evaluation across all folds. This approach ensures that performance metrics accurately reflect the model’s ability to classify both majority and minority classes, making it particularly useful for imbalanced datasets like this one.

4.2 Hold-Out Validation¶

Holdout validation is used in this task because it provides a reliable and computationally efficient method for evaluating model performance while preserving an unseen test set for the final assessment. It also helps prevent data leakage and overfitting, as using the entire dataset for training without setting aside a test set could lead to an overly optimistic performance estimate. By holding out a separate test set, we ensure that the final model is evaluated on completely unseen data, providing a realistic measure of its generalization ability.

4.3 Combined Approach: K-Fold and Holdout Evaluation¶

This hybrid approach combines stratified k-fold cross-validation and holdout validation to ensure a fair and unbiased final assessment of the model. First, stratified k-fold cross-validation is applied to the training data to evaluate multiple model configurations, fine-tune hyperparameters, and select the best-performing model. This process helps reduce variance and improve generalization, making the model more reliable.

Once the optimal model is identified, it is evaluated on the holdout test set, which remains unseen throughout training and validation. This final evaluation provides an objective measure of real-world performance, ensuring the model generalizes effectively without overfitting to the validation set.

5. Preparing Your Data¶

In this section, we will prepare the dataset for model training by computing class weights and formatting the data for input. This process involves calculating class weights to handle class imbalance, normalizing features to ensure consistent data scaling, and splitting the dataset into training, validation, and test sets. Additionally, the data will be explicitly converted into NumPy arrays, as we will be using NumPy functions, and TensorFlow accepts NumPy input for efficient processing.

5.1 Computing Class Weights¶

First, we compute the class weights using the compute_class_weight function from Scikit-Learn. This function adjusts class weights based on their frequency in the dataset, assigning higher weights to less frequent classes and lower weights to more common ones. It does this by dividing the total number of samples by the product of the number of classes and the number of samples in each class, ensuring that minority classes receive greater importance during training.

After computing the class weights, we convert the resulting NumPy array into a dictionary so that it can be used in TensorFlow during model training. We perform this step before normalization and data splitting to ensure that the computed weights accurately reflect the full dataset distribution.

5.3 Holdout Validation¶

Before performing holdout validation, we first need to one-hot encode the fetal_health labels to adjust them to start from 0, as they currently begin at 1. We achieve this using “to_categorical” from TensorFlow.

In [87]:

# Convert target (y) to one-hot encoding

From this, 10% will be used as the validation set, which helps fine-tune and evaluate the model during training. The remaining 20% will serve as the test set, which is reserved for the final evaluation to assess the model’s performance on unseen data.

6. Developing a Baseline Model¶

Here, we will define a naive baseline as a reference for comparison and develop a baseline model that outperforms it. This serves as a starting point for the classification task, providing an initial benchmark for model evaluation and improvement.

6.1 Naive Baseline¶

Before starting, we need to define a naive baseline, which is a simple, often overly simplistic model used as a reference point for comparison when evaluating more complex models. Although naive baselines make simplistic assumptions, they are useful for establishing a minimum performance benchmark.

For this task, we will use the “DummyClassifier" from Scikit-Learn along with “balanced_accuracy_score”, “f1_score”, “precision_score”, and “recall_score” as evaluation metrics. We will apply the “most_frequent” strategy, which always predicts the most frequent class in the training set. To prevent data leakage, we will train the naive baseline using only the training set rather than the entire dataset. The test set will remain exclusive for final evaluation, ensuring a fair comparison against later models. Using the entire dataset for the naive baseline would give it an unfair advantage, as real models will only be trained on a subset of the data.

In [92]:

naive_f1 = f1_score(y_val.argmax(axis=1), y_dummy_pred, average='macro')

As seen from the results above, the naive baseline model has a very low balanced accuracy of 0.33 because it predicts only the most frequent class, completely ignoring the minority classes. The precision of 0.93 is misleadingly high since the model rarely predicts minority classes, resulting in very few false positives but many false negatives. The recall of 0.33 is extremely poor, indicating that the model fails to detect most minority class instances, further confirming its bias toward the majority class and its inability to generalize. Additionally, the macro F1 score of 0.29, which balances precision and recall, reflects the overall poor performance of the model despite its seemingly high precision.

Since the precision and recall metrics are skewed due to the "most_frequent" strategy used by the Dummy Classifier, which never predicts the minority classes, they do not provide an accurate measure of performance. As a result, we will focus on comparing the naive baseline and the baseline model using balanced accuracy and macro F1 score, as these metrics offer a fairer assessment of overall model performance.

6.2 Baseline Model¶

After obtaining the naive baseline performance, we can proceed with developing the baseline model. This model should be designed to outperform the naive baseline while maintaining simplicity. To achieve this, we will use Keras to build our models, starting with a sequential model composed of dense layers. However, before constructing the baseline model, we must first determine several key hyperparameters that will influence its performance.

6.2.1 Number of Layers¶

The number of layers in a neural network determines how well the model can capture complex patterns and relationships within the data. Each layer computes a weighted sum of inputs and passes it through an activation function in the hidden layers. The choice of layers depends on the dataset’s complexity. A single hidden layer is sufficient to approximate any function that maps one finite space to another, enabling the model to learn nonlinear relationships and intricate patterns. Adding a second hidden layer allows the network to approximate complex decision boundaries with arbitrary accuracy, increasing its flexibility. Since our dataset contains complex nonlinear patterns, we will begin with a single hidden layer for our baseline model. If necessary, additional layers can be introduced later to improve performance.

6.2.2 Number of Hidden Neurons¶

The number of hidden neurons is determined based on the size of the input features and the nature of the task. The input layer contains as many neurons as there are features in the dataset, while the output layer corresponds to the number of class labels, as this is a multi-class classification problem. A common rule of thumb suggests that the number of hidden neurons should fall between the size of the input and output layers. One approach is to set it to approximately two-thirds of the input layer size plus the output layer size, which in this case results in 17 neurons. Another guideline is that the hidden layer should have fewer than twice the size of the input layer, which would be around 40 neurons.

Since we are building a baseline model that only needs to surpass the naive baseline, we will start with 16 hidden neurons, as it is a reasonable value. It is smaller than the input layer, close to the two-thirds rule, and well within the upper bound of 40. Therefore, our baseline model will consist of an input layer with 21 neurons, corresponding to the twenty-one features in our dataset, a hidden layer with 16 neurons, and an output layer with 3 neurons representing the class labels.

6.2.3 Activation Functions¶

The activation function maps inputs to the desired output by transforming the weighted sum of inputs plus bias into a final output value. Without activation functions, neural networks would behave like simple linear regression models, limiting their ability to capture nonlinear relationships essential for solving real-world problems. ReLU (Rectified Linear Unit) is one of the most popular activation functions, as it enables neural networks to learn complex patterns efficiently and is widely used in deep learning applications.

The last-layer activation function is responsible for generating the final predictions of the model. It is critical because it determines how the output values are interpreted. Since this is a multiclass, single-label classification problem, the standard approach is to use the softmax activation function in the last layer. Softmax converts the raw output values into a probability distribution, ensuring that the sum of all output values equals one. The class with the highest probability is selected as the model’s final prediction, making softmax ideal for multiclass classification tasks.

6.2.4 Loss Function¶

The loss function quantifies how far off the network’s predictions are from the actual target values by measuring the disparity between predicted and true outcomes. It guides the training process by computing errors and influencing parameter updates through backpropagation. In essence, the loss function evaluates how well the model is learning to represent the dataset. For this multiclass classification problem, we will use “categorical_crossentropy", which is the most commonly used loss function for such tasks. "categorical_crossentropy" computes the difference between the predicted probability distribution and the true class labels, making it an effective choice for optimizing multi-class models.

6.2.5 Optimization Configuration¶

Optimizers adjust the model’s weights and learning rates to minimize error and improve performance. An optimization algorithm determines the values of the parameters (weights) that minimize the loss function when mapping inputs to outputs. Its primary role is to fine-tune the neural network’s parameters, ensuring the model learns effectively and converges to an optimal solution.

There are various types of optimizers, each with distinct update rules, learning rates, and momentum strategies. Some common ones include Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD), Adam, and RMSprop. For our baseline model, we will use RMSprop with its default learning rate, as it is a widely effective choice for handling different types of machine learning problems and ensuring stable convergence.

6.2.6 Epochs¶

An epoch refers to one complete pass of the entire training dataset through the model during training. The number of epochs is a critical hyperparameter, as it determines how many times the learning algorithm will iterate over the dataset. Training for a single epoch is usually insufficient to capture all the patterns in the data. By running multiple epochs, the model gradually learns and improves its performance as it refines the weights through repeated updates. For our baseline model, we will start with 30 epochs, as this provides a reasonable starting point. If necessary, we can adjust this number based on the model’s performance and convergence behavior.

6.2.7 Batch Size¶

A batch refers to a subset of the training data that is processed together during one forward pass and one backward pass of the neural network because the entire dataset is often too large to process all at once, it is divided into smaller groups called batches. Batch size is a hyperparameter that defines the number of training examples included in one batch. It determines how much data is processed before the model updates its weights. Choosing the optimal batch size is crucial as it impacts training efficiency and model performance, allowing for better resource utilization and faster convergence. For starters, we can go with 32 as a good starting point as it provides a balance between stability and training speed and we can adjust accordingly later on based on the model’s performance

6.2.8 Structure Overview¶

For our baseline model, we will use Keras to define a simple neural network with:

  • Input Layer: Consists of 21 features (matching the dataset's feature count).
  • Hidden Layer: A single dense layer with 16 neurons, using the ReLU activation function to introduce non-linearity and help the model learn complex patterns.
  • Output Layer: A dense layer with 3 neurons, corresponding to the number of class labels. This layer uses the softmax activation function, which converts raw output values into a probability distribution, ensuring that the predicted class has the highest probability.

We will compile the model with:

  • Optimizer: RMSprop (using its default learning rate).
  • Loss Function: Categorical crossentropy, which is well-suited for multiclass classification.

We will evaluate the model with:

  • Balanced accuracy (imported from sklearn).
  • Precision, recall, and macro F1 score (calculated using TensorFlow).

For training, we will start with 30 epochs and a batch size of 32, adjusting these values based on the model’s performance. We will train the model using the training set and evaluate it using the validation set, keeping the test set unseen until the final model evaluation to ensure an unbiased assessment of generalization.

6.2.9 Implementation¶

Since we will be repeating the implementation process throughout this study with different models, we can create functions to streamline the workflow and improve efficiency.

In [44]:
# Function to compile the model with dynamic optimizer selection
def compile_model(model, learning_rate=0.001, optimizer_name="rmsprop"):
    # Choose the optimizer based on the optimizer_name parameter
    if optimizer_name == "rmsprop":
        optimizer = RMSprop(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    elif optimizer_name == "adam":
        optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    elif optimizer_name == "sgd":
        optimizer = SGD(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    else:
        raise ValueError(f"Unsupported optimizer: {optimizer_name}")

    # Compile the model with the chosen optimizer
    model.compile(
        optimizer=optimizer,
        loss="categorical_crossentropy",
        metrics=[
            Precision(name="precision"),
            Recall(name="recall"),
            F1Score(name="f1_score", average="macro")
        ]
    )

# Function to train the model (with flexible epochs for overfitting)
def train_model(model, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, epochs=30, batch_size=32, class_weight=None):
    history = model.fit(
        X_train, y_train,
        epochs=epochs,  
        batch_size=batch_size,
        validation_data=(X_val, y_val),
        class_weight=class_weight,
        verbose=0
    )
    return history

# Function to evaluate the model
def evaluate_model(model, X_val, y_val):
    results = model.evaluate(X_val, y_val, batch_size=32, verbose=0)
    return results

# Function to get class predictions
def get_predictions(model, X_val, y_val):
    y_pred = model.predict(X_val, verbose=0).argmax(axis=1)
    y_true = y_val.argmax(axis=1)  # Convert one-hot labels back to integer class labels
    return y_pred, y_true

# Function to print evaluation results
def print_evaluation_results(balanced_acc, precision, recall, f1_score, y_pred):
    print(f"Balanced Accuracy: {balanced_acc:.2f}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.2f}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall:.2f}")
    print(f"F1 Score (Macro): {f1_score:.2f}")

    # Print class distribution in predictions
    unique, counts = np.unique(y_pred, return_counts=True)
    print("Prediction Distribution:", dict(zip(unique, counts)))

# Function to plot training vs validation loss
def plot_loss(training_history, plot_title="Training vs Validation Loss"):
    # Extract training and validation loss
    loss = training_history.history['loss']  # Training loss
    val_loss = training_history.history['val_loss']  # Validation loss

    # Get the number of epochs
    epochs = range(1, len(loss) + 1)

    # Plot training & validation loss as points and lines
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'r.-', label='Training Loss')  # Red points with line
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b.-', label='Validation Loss')  # Blue points with line
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.title(plot_title)  # Dynamic title
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

8. Finalizing the Model Architecture¶

Before applying regularization and fine-tuning the overfitting model, it is essential to first establish a stable and well-defined model architecture. In this section, we will determine the optimal model structure and select the appropriate number of hidden neurons to ensure effective learning.

8.1 Network Architecture¶

In our current setup, the baseline model uses a single hidden layer with 16 neurons. This model performs adequately but does not reach optimal performance. On the other hand, our overfitting model uses two hidden layers and performs well on the training data, but it suffers from overfitting, indicating that the model has too much capacity for the data. To compare these two architectures, we will use Stratified K-Fold Cross-Validation to evaluate both the single hidden layer model and the two hidden layer model. This will allow us to compute and compare several key metrics (balanced accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score) to determine which architecture performs better.

The first step in this process is to define a function that creates the model with either a single hidden layer or two hidden layers, depending on the architecture we want to test. For the single hidden layer model, we will use 16 neurons, while for the two hidden layer model, we will use 32 neurons in the first hidden layer and 16 neurons in the second hidden layer.

In [96]:
# Define 5-Fold Cross-Validation
kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

# Function to Create Models
def create_model(num_hidden_layers=1):
    model = Sequential([
        Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1],)),  # Input layer (21 features)
    ])
    
    # Add one or two hidden layers based on the parameter
    if num_hidden_layers == 1:
        model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
    else:
        model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))

    model.add(Dense(3, activation='softmax'))  # Output layer for 3 classes
    
    return model

Once the model architecture is defined, we will run Stratified K-Fold Cross-Validation to evaluate both models. Stratified K-Fold ensures that the class distribution is preserved in each fold, which is important when working with imbalanced datasets. We will compute the performance metrics for each fold, and then average the results to identify which model architecture is more effective. This process will help us compare the performance of a single hidden layer model against a two hidden layer model to determine which configuration best suits our dataset.

In [97]:
# Store metrics across all folds for both models
results_1_layer = {'balanced_acc': [], 'precision': [], 'recall': [], 'f1_score': []}
results_2_layers = {'balanced_acc': [], 'precision': [], 'recall': [], 'f1_score': []}

# Perform K-Fold Cross-Validation
for train_idx, val_idx in kfold.split(X_train, y_train.argmax(axis=1)):  
    X_train_fold, X_val_fold = X_train[train_idx], X_train[val_idx]
    y_train_fold, y_val_fold = y_train[train_idx], y_train[val_idx]

    # Train and Evaluate 1 Hidden Layer Model
    model_1 = create_model(num_hidden_layers=1)
    compile_model(model_1)
    model_1_history = train_model(model_1, X_train_fold, y_train_fold, X_val_fold, y_val_fold, epochs=100, class_weight=class_weight_dict)
    model_1_results = evaluate_model(model_1, X_val_fold, y_val_fold)
    y_pred_1, y_true_1 = get_predictions(model_1, X_val_fold, y_val_fold)

8.2 Number of Hidden Neurons¶

Once the model architecture is finalized, the next step is to tune the number of hidden neurons. The number of neurons in each hidden layer plays a crucial role in the model’s ability to learn from the data. Too few neurons can lead to underfitting, while too many can result in overfitting.

To find the optimal configuration, we will update the "create_model()" function to experiment with different neuron configurations. These configurations include 64 → 32, 32 → 16, and 16 → 8 neurons, which represent varying levels of model complexity. The 64 → 32 configuration allows for a more complex model, while 32 → 16 offers a balanced approach, and 16 → 8 simplifies the model further. Testing these configurations will help us determine the right balance between capacity and generalization.

9. Regularization and Hyperparameters Tuning¶

In this section, we will explore techniques of regularization and hyperparameter tuning to enhance the model’s generalization and performance, while also prevent overfitting. This step is crucial to ensure that the model not only fits the training data well but also generalizes effectively to unseen data. Here, we will be using stratified k-fold cross validation to find out the optimal value for each hyperparameters. So before we begin, we need to update and solidify our "create_model()" function and create a "run_kfold()" function to facilitate easier cross-validation.

In [102]:
# Function to Create Models
def create_model(input_shape, dropout_rate=None, l2_value=None):
    model = Sequential()

    # Input layer
    model.add(Input(shape=(input_shape,)))  
    
    # First hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_value) if l2_value else None))
    if dropout_rate:
        model.add(Dropout(dropout_rate))  # Apply dropout if specified

    # Second hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_value) if l2_value else None))
    if dropout_rate:
        model.add(Dropout(dropout_rate))  # Apply dropout if specified

    # Output layer for 3 classes
    model.add(Dense(3, activation='softmax')) 
    
    return model

def run_kfold(neurons_1=32, neurons_2=16, dropout_rate=0.1, l2_value=0.001, learning_rate=0.001, optimizer_name="rmsprop", batch_size=32, epochs=30):
    fold_results = {'balanced_acc': [], 'precision': [], 'recall': [], 'f1_score': []}

    for train_idx, val_idx in kfold.split(X_train, y_train.argmax(axis=1)):  
        X_train_fold, X_val_fold = np.array(X_train[train_idx]), np.array(X_train[val_idx])
        y_train_fold, y_val_fold = np.array(y_train[train_idx]), np.array(y_train[val_idx])

        # Create the model
        model = create_model(X_train.shape[1], dropout_rate=dropout_rate, l2_value=l2_value)

        # Compile the model
        compile_model(model, learning_rate=learning_rate, optimizer_name=optimizer_name)

        # Train the model
        model_history = train_model(model, X_train_fold, y_train_fold, X_val_fold, y_val_fold, epochs=epochs, batch_size=batch_size)

        # Evaluate the model
        model_results = evaluate_model(model, X_val_fold, y_val_fold)

        # Get Predictions and Compute Balanced Accuracy
        y_pred, y_true = get_predictions(model, X_val_fold, y_val_fold)
        balanced_acc = balanced_accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
        
        # Store Metrics
        fold_results['balanced_acc'].append(balanced_acc)
        fold_results['precision'].append(model_results[1])  # Precision
        fold_results['recall'].append(model_results[2])  # Recall
        fold_results['f1_score'].append(model_results[3])  # F1-Score

    # Compute Averages
    return {key: np.mean(val) for key, val in fold_results.items()}

9.1 Regularization¶

Regularization refers to a set of techniques used to prevent overfitting and improve a model’s ability to generalize to new data. It involves adding a penalty term to the loss function during training, which discourages the model from becoming too complex or having excessively large parameter values. This helps control the model’s tendency to fit noise in the training data. In this study, we will examine two forms of regularization: dropout and L2 regularization, both of which help enhance the model’s robustness and performance on unseen data.

9.1.1 L2 Regularization¶

L1 and L2 regularization are techniques used to penalize large weights in a model to prevent overfitting and improve generalization. They achieve this by adding a penalty term to the loss function, which helps constrain the model’s capacity and prevents it from becoming too complex.

In this task, we will use L2 regularization, as it is the most commonly applied method and serves as a strong default choice for preventing overfitting. To determine the optimal L2 value, we will perform cross-validation across multiple values to identify the best-performing regularization strength.

9.1.2 Dropout¶

Dropout is a regularization technique that helps prevent overfitting by randomly deactivating a fraction of neurons during training. This forces the model to rely on multiple independent neurons, preventing co-adaptation where neurons become overly dependent on each other and making the model more robust. During training, a specified percentage of neurons are randomly dropped, while during testing, all neurons are used, but their outputs are scaled to compensate. Dropout encourages the model to learn more generalizable features, improving its performance on unseen data.

9.2 Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Hyperparameter tuning is the process of selecting the optimal values for a model’s hyperparameters, which are settings that control the learning process. These include parameters such as the learning rate, number of neurons, batch size, and optimizer used by the model. The goal of hyperparameter tuning is to identify the values that lead to the best performance by improving generalization and minimizing overfitting.

For this study, we will tune learning rates, optimizers, batch size, and epochs, while using stratified K-fold cross validation to ensure that the selected hyperparameters are optimized and provide consistent performance across different data splits.

9.2.1 Learning rate¶

The learning rate is a critical hyperparameter that controls how much to change the model in response to the estimated error each time the model weights are updated. A too high learning rate may result in an unstable training process while a too low learning rate can result in a long training process that could get stuck

Smaller batch sizes may result in noisier updates but could help the model generalize better, while larger batch sizes offer more stable updates but could lead to slower convergence. By testing different batch sizes, we aim to identify the one that provides the best balance between training efficiency and model performance.

9.2.4 Epochs¶

For epochs, we will use early stopping instead of manually determining the optimal value. Early stopping automatically halts training once the model's performance on the validation set stops improving, preventing unnecessary training and reducing computational cost and time consumption.

Additionally, early stopping helps prevent overfitting by ensuring the model does not continue learning patterns specific to the training data that do not generalize well to unseen data. However, we will set the maximum number of epochs to 100, allowing the model to train for up to 100 epochs unless early stopping triggers an earlier stop.

11. Conclusion¶

In this project, we successfully developed and optimized a deep learning model for fetal health classification, utilizing Stratified K-Fold Cross-Validation, regularization, and hyperparameter tuning to refine the model’s generalization ability. The final model achieved a balanced accuracy of 0.73, precision of 0.89, recall of 0.86, and an F1 score of 0.72, demonstrating a significant improvement over the baseline model while mitigating some of the overfitting seen in earlier models. These improvements confirm that our tuning and optimization strategies effectively enhanced classification performance, particularly in distinguishing Normal and Pathological cases.

Despite these advances, the model still exhibited some overfitting, especially in classifying Suspect cases, which remained the most challenging category. The confusion matrix revealed that many Suspect cases were misclassified as Normal, suggesting that the model struggles to differentiate between borderline fetal health conditions. This issue is likely due to the small dataset size and class imbalance, where the model learns patterns from the majority class (Normal) more effectively than from the minority classes (Suspect and Pathological). Expanding the dataset with more diverse and representative samples could help improve the model's ability to recognize more subtle differences between classes.

Another challenge was the fluctuations in validation loss, indicating that while the model was able to generalize better than the overfitting model, there was still room for improvement. Additional regularization techniques, such as stronger dropout strategies, hybrid L1-L2 regularization, or advanced learning rate decay schedules, could help stabilize training further. The model's ability to detect Pathological cases was fairly strong, but there were still some critical misclassifications, which could have real-world consequences in medical settings. A greater focus on recall for high-risk cases could help ensure that fewer critical conditions are missed.

One major limitation of this study was the small dataset size, which restricted the model’s ability to fully generalize. Deep learning models typically require large amounts of training data, and with only 2,126 records, the dataset was relatively limited. A larger dataset would likely improve model performance and reduce sensitivity to noise in the data. Furthermore, the class imbalance issue negatively impacted the model’s ability to correctly classify Suspect cases, as the model was biased toward predicting the dominant class. Addressing this imbalance through class-weighting, resampling techniques like SMOTE, or data augmentation could help improve classification performance across all classes.

Despite these challenges, this project demonstrated that carefully tuning hyperparameters, applying regularization, and optimizing training strategies can significantly improve fetal health classification models. While this study was limited to fully connected neural networks, future work could explore more advanced architectures, such as CNNs for feature extraction from CTG signals, RNNs or LSTMs for handling temporal dependencies in fetal monitoring data, or transformer-based models for more robust feature learning. Implementing ensemble learning techniques could also improve the model’s overall robustness and reduce misclassifications.

Future improvements could also focus on incorporating additional real-world clinical data, which would provide a more diverse dataset for training. This could help improve the model’s reliability in detecting less common but high-risk fetal conditions. By improving the dataset and fine-tuning model architecture, this approach has the potential to be applied in clinical decision support systems, aiding healthcare professionals in identifying fetal distress and improving maternal and neonatal health outcomes.

Overall, our final model successfully improved upon the baseline model while avoiding the excessive overfitting seen in the overfitting model. While the challenge of correctly classifying Suspect cases remains, the study provides a strong foundation for further refinements. With enhancements in data balancing, architectural improvements, and additional regularization techniques, this model could become an even more powerful tool for fetal health assessment, contributing to more accurate and timely diagnoses in real-world clinical settings.
